No, no!

491
01:01:46,462 --> 01:01:48,657
- I could show. I could.
- Show what?

492
01:01:48,831 --> 01:01:52,267
You can't. They're people.
You can't use people.

493
01:02:02,511 --> 01:02:04,206
All right...

494
01:02:07,049 --> 01:02:09,609
Patrick, show me
what's in your pouch.

495
01:02:13,188 --> 01:02:15,019
Please.

496
01:02:17,826 --> 01:02:20,989
Patrick, show me
what's in your pouch.

497
01:02:30,506 --> 01:02:34,340
They're just plastic toys.
Plazteck people.

498
01:02:34,510 --> 01:02:38,037
- They're just completely plazteck.
- OK.

499
01:02:38,213 --> 01:02:41,546
- That's fine.
- Plazteck.

500
01:02:41,717 --> 01:02:45,949
- Yes. Thank you. Let me see.
- Plazteck.

501
01:02:48,390 --> 01:02:50,824
Let me see.

502
01:03:26,995 --> 01:03:29,828
They're just people.

503
01:03:34,169 --> 01:03:38,731
Why don't you two work this out?
But no more fighting, OK?

504
01:03:38,907 --> 01:03:42,536
- All right.
- Go catch up with your class.

505
01:04:01,396 --> 01:04:03,330
"It's just like having a child. "

506
01:04:03,932 --> 01:04:07,163
"Every time I'm away from him,
I worry that he's OK."

507
01:04:07,736 --> 01:04:09,727
"I come home and open the door"

508
01:04:09,905 --> 01:04:11,839
"and worry about what I will find. "

509
01:04:12,007 --> 01:04:15,465
"But he's a man.
I can't treat him like a baby. "

510
01:04:17,412 --> 01:04:19,403
Good. Sam.

511
01:04:20,182 --> 01:04:21,410
"JFK."

512
01:04:21,583 --> 01:04:25,349
"JFK was about
the youngest man ever president. "

513
01:04:25,520 --> 01:04:28,318
"There were little kids
in the White House. "

514
01:04:30,959 --> 01:04:34,622
Mum, can Patrick
please spend the night?

515
01:04:34,796 --> 01:04:37,128
- Yeah, I think so.
- Spend the night?

516
01:04:37,299 --> 01:04:39,267
It's a wife.

517
01:04:41,136 --> 01:04:42,398
Excuse me.

518
01:04:42,571 --> 01:04:45,597
- That's great. Come on.
- Look at 'em.

519
01:05:14,603 --> 01:05:16,571
Who will she be?

520
01:05:17,706 --> 01:05:20,573
- What is that?
- It's a wife.

521
01:05:20,742 --> 01:05:25,270
A wife? My mother should
choose me a wife.

522
01:05:25,447 --> 01:05:27,881
But your mother's not here.

523
01:05:28,050 --> 01:05:32,248
I've been thinking about
settling down my own self.

524
01:05:41,930 --> 01:05:45,866
It's gone. The cupboard's gone.

525
01:05:48,236 --> 01:05:49,863
Who would take it?

526
01:05:56,311 --> 01:05:58,779
- Where is it?
- Where's what?

527
01:05:58,947 --> 01:06:02,383
- The cupboard, butt-head.
- Who gave you that cupboard?

528
01:06:02,551 --> 01:06:06,419
Please, where's the cupboard?
Gili, please.

529
01:06:06,588 --> 01:06:08,954
Where's my rat ball?

530
01:06:35,283 --> 01:06:37,444
Where? Please?

531
01:06:37,619 --> 01:06:39,814
In the crawlspace.

532
01:07:00,375 --> 01:07:02,138
Damn.

533
01:07:04,913 --> 01:07:08,872
The key! Where's the key?

534
01:07:09,050 --> 01:07:11,610
There was no key. I swear.

535
01:07:31,940 --> 01:07:36,240
You mean, we've got to live
here forever? Little like this?

536
01:07:36,411 --> 01:07:41,144
No new wife for Little Bear?
No baby? He needs a baby.

537
01:07:41,316 --> 01:07:43,341
I could look for another key.

538
01:07:45,487 --> 01:07:50,151
I want to go home. We've just got
the railroad coming through town

539
01:07:50,325 --> 01:07:52,987
and we've got a new doctor,
a good doctor.

540
01:07:53,161 --> 01:07:57,154
Hell, it's 1879. I'm living
at the dawn of a new century.

541
01:08:01,336 --> 01:08:03,804
Now I know what
you was talking about.

542
01:08:03,972 --> 01:08:07,237
God sure do play with men, all right.

543
01:08:07,409 --> 01:08:09,934
There is no god here.

544
01:08:23,525 --> 01:08:26,050
Come on, Gili!

545
01:08:28,263 --> 01:08:29,924
- Bye, Mum. Bye, Dad.
- Bye, guys.

546
01:08:30,098 --> 01:08:31,656
Bye, Mum.

547
01:09:11,106 --> 01:09:13,233
Disgusting display.

548
01:09:14,276 --> 01:09:16,744
They do this in front of you children?

549
01:09:16,912 --> 01:09:21,542
- It's not reaI.
- It's reaI all right. It's reaI.

550
01:09:21,716 --> 01:09:24,116
Let's change to
the Discovery ChanneI.

551
01:09:26,621 --> 01:09:30,022
<i>...roaming the great savannahs
of Africa.</i>

552
01:09:32,527 --> 01:09:34,722
Let me see that clicker.

553
01:09:46,808 --> 01:09:50,869
Apaches! The ugliest Redskins
that ever walked the earth!

554
01:09:56,685 --> 01:09:58,744
Get 'em, boys! Hell, yeah!

555
01:10:45,066 --> 01:10:48,524
Little Bear? Amigo?

556
01:11:43,992 --> 01:11:47,655
- He's alive.
- I wish we had Tommy.

557
01:11:48,897 --> 01:11:53,357
- You do not have the key.
- Can you take the arrow out?

558
01:11:56,071 --> 01:11:58,835
Blood will flow. Get me husks.

559
01:11:59,674 --> 01:12:01,198
We have no husks.

560
01:12:25,500 --> 01:12:27,297
Leave me.

561
01:12:43,585 --> 01:12:45,951
Boys?

562
01:12:48,690 --> 01:12:50,453
Time for bed.

563
01:12:50,625 --> 01:12:53,788
- Can you turn out the light, please?
- Sure.

564
01:12:58,233 --> 01:13:00,758
I feeI like I haven't seen you
in days.

565
01:13:00,935 --> 01:13:05,031
- Cartoon day tomorrow.
- I don't think we'll watch, thanks.

566
01:13:09,644 --> 01:13:11,737
- Good night.
- Good night, Mum.

567
01:13:11,913 --> 01:13:13,710
- Night, Patrick.
- Night, Janie.

568
01:13:13,882 --> 01:13:16,578
If you hear noises under the floor,
it's Gili's rat.

569
01:13:16,751 --> 01:13:19,117
- What?
- He escaped.

570
01:13:19,287 --> 01:13:22,779
Dad pulled up your floorboards
but he couldn't get him.

571
01:13:22,957 --> 01:13:24,754
That rat's under my floor?

572
01:13:24,926 --> 01:13:29,226
Maybe. He might have moved on.
If we're lucky, he moved out.

573
01:13:29,397 --> 01:13:31,490
- Oh, no.
- I know.

574
01:13:31,666 --> 01:13:33,600
Good night, guys.

575
01:13:42,844 --> 01:13:47,144
- Do you think he'll be OK?
- A rat will eat at a wounded man.

576
01:13:47,315 --> 01:13:50,580
Now we can't go to sleep at all.

577
01:13:52,153 --> 01:13:53,381
We'll take turns.

578
01:13:53,555 --> 01:13:56,991
If you go first,
I'll give you a million dollars.

579
01:15:00,455 --> 01:15:05,392
Wake up! I hear the rat! Get up!

580
01:15:40,828 --> 01:15:43,956
- It's the key!
- Get it!

581
01:15:44,132 --> 01:15:45,793
Hold this.

582
01:15:49,003 --> 01:15:51,062
Watch out.

583
01:16:06,688 --> 01:16:08,656
Oh, no!

584
01:16:09,357 --> 01:16:11,416
Let me go.

585
01:16:21,769 --> 01:16:25,671
I am too big. I am too big!

586
01:16:25,840 --> 01:16:29,401
See if you can get under
that loose floorboard there.

587
01:16:32,380 --> 01:16:35,975
There's an animaI, a big animaI.
Move fast.

588
01:16:48,329 --> 01:16:51,264
Do you see a way? Is there a hole?

589
01:16:51,432 --> 01:16:53,900
Yes, I see one.

590
01:16:54,802 --> 01:16:56,736
- Omri?
- Yeah?

591
01:16:56,904 --> 01:17:00,533
- What are also dangers?
- Everything.

592
01:17:06,314 --> 01:17:09,374
Did he take his bow and arrow?
And his knife?

593
01:17:21,562 --> 01:17:23,029
Little Bear!

594
01:17:32,507 --> 01:17:34,134
Where is he?

595
01:17:39,113 --> 01:17:40,808
Little Bear!

596
01:17:48,022 --> 01:17:49,956
I hear him! Over there!

597
01:17:57,932 --> 01:18:00,526
- Where is he?
- Little Bear, come back.

598
01:18:24,625 --> 01:18:26,855
Come back, come back!

599
01:18:29,864 --> 01:18:32,230
- What was that?
- I don't know.

600
01:18:32,400 --> 01:18:34,732
Please, Little Bear, come back.

601
01:18:34,902 --> 01:18:37,336
Why won't he come?

602
01:18:39,240 --> 01:18:41,208
<i>Omri?</i>

603
01:19:11,672 --> 01:19:13,731
I got him!

604
01:19:27,588 --> 01:19:28,953
It's you again.

605
01:19:31,292 --> 01:19:34,022
I do pick my moments to fall asleep.

606
01:19:34,195 --> 01:19:37,096
A great Minnie whining overhead.

607
01:19:37,265 --> 01:19:40,428
Thought I was a goner.
Perhaps I am a goner. Did I die?

608
01:19:40,601 --> 01:19:43,263
No. You're dreaming again.

609
01:19:48,142 --> 01:19:51,043
There's two of you now,
are there? Good show.

610
01:19:51,212 --> 01:19:54,045
Well, take me to him.
The elegant Injun?

611
01:19:54,215 --> 01:19:55,944
No, it's another.

612
01:20:05,059 --> 01:20:07,687
That's clever. Hello again.

613
01:20:09,130 --> 01:20:11,098
- The bleeding stopped.
- Yes. Good.

614
01:20:11,265 --> 01:20:14,166
He needs a blood transfusion,
but I'm not prepared for that.

615
01:20:16,070 --> 01:20:19,471
- A bullet, was it?
- Arrow.

616
01:20:20,942 --> 01:20:23,001
Lucky it missed his heart and lung.

617
01:20:29,584 --> 01:20:31,711
The cotton's damp.

618
01:20:33,087 --> 01:20:36,181
So, you're a paI of his, are you?

619
01:20:37,792 --> 01:20:39,350
Amigo.

620
01:21:00,248 --> 01:21:02,944
That should just about do it.

621
01:21:03,117 --> 01:21:07,019
Look, keep a close watch on him.
Plenty of water.

622
01:21:07,188 --> 01:21:09,588
He could use a doctor's care.

623
01:21:14,295 --> 01:21:16,024
There's a doctor in his town.

624
01:21:18,866 --> 01:21:21,892
- No.
- When he wakes up.

625
01:21:22,069 --> 01:21:23,627
Not yet.

626
01:21:29,210 --> 01:21:31,235
It's time for them to go home.

627
01:21:32,647 --> 01:21:35,616
Good. That will do.
He needs to sleep.

628
01:21:35,783 --> 01:21:38,980
Well, I best be getting back.

629
01:21:39,153 --> 01:21:42,554
We'll all be waking up soon enough.
I suggest a drop of brandy.

630
01:21:44,425 --> 01:21:47,724
- Thank you.
- You're welcome, mate.

631
01:21:47,895 --> 01:21:50,864
Buckles keep catching on my doodah.

632
01:22:08,316 --> 01:22:10,079
Omri!

633
01:22:19,493 --> 01:22:21,825
I'm so ashamed of myself.

634
01:22:28,736 --> 01:22:30,863
I hurt you.

635
01:22:31,038 --> 01:22:33,836
What are you talking about?

636
01:22:38,145 --> 01:22:40,511
Did I hear somebody mention brandy?

637
01:23:35,236 --> 01:23:37,500
No, Omri.

638
01:23:37,671 --> 01:23:40,139
She has her life.

639
01:23:40,307 --> 01:23:43,140
She has a family, a clan.

640
01:23:44,612 --> 01:23:46,546
Maybe a husband and a child.

641
01:23:47,515 --> 01:23:50,177
I don't want you to be alone.

642
01:23:50,351 --> 01:23:52,785
I will be with my people.

643
01:24:03,464 --> 01:24:05,728
I will be with you
when the sun rises?

644
01:24:07,601 --> 01:24:09,262
One more time.

645
01:24:50,945 --> 01:24:53,778
Hey, son. When we go back,

646
01:24:53,948 --> 01:24:57,247
are we going back to the last
thing we remember or ahead?

647
01:24:57,418 --> 01:24:59,716
I don't know.

648
01:25:00,354 --> 01:25:02,948
I hope it's forwards.
How about you, Little Bear?

649
01:25:03,123 --> 01:25:05,683
Little Bear, where are you headed?

650
01:25:07,328 --> 01:25:09,888
I was on the journey
with my brother's son.

651
01:25:10,064 --> 01:25:12,225
I think I will wake up in the woods.

652
01:25:12,399 --> 01:25:16,802
It is quiet
and the nights are getting cold.

653
01:25:16,971 --> 01:25:19,462
I can almost smell the trees.

654
01:25:20,875 --> 01:25:24,675
I can almost smell them, too.
Like I'm part Indian now my own self.

655
01:25:26,313 --> 01:25:29,476
If you were my nephew, it'd be
time to walk you through the forest.

656
01:25:29,650 --> 01:25:30,912
I would go.

657
01:25:49,203 --> 01:25:51,330
It is difficult.

658
01:25:53,707 --> 01:25:56,198
You would live by yourself,

659
01:25:56,377 --> 01:25:58,709
care for yourself.

660
01:26:32,980 --> 01:26:37,440
We would traveI for days,
tell stories,

661
01:26:37,618 --> 01:26:39,518
hunt and fish.

662
01:26:40,521 --> 01:26:43,046
I'd leave you and return
to the village.

663
01:26:43,223 --> 01:26:45,418
You must live alone for one season.

664
01:26:45,593 --> 01:26:49,051
You would learn to live in harmony
with Mother Nature...

665
01:26:49,229 --> 01:26:53,928
...the two-legged,
the four-legged, the winged.

666
01:26:55,102 --> 01:26:57,662
When the seasons change,

667
01:26:57,838 --> 01:27:00,204
my nephew would come home.

668
01:27:02,009 --> 01:27:05,536
- I would be waiting for you.
- Little Bear...

669
01:27:05,713 --> 01:27:08,238
We would have a great celebration

670
01:27:08,415 --> 01:27:11,646
because you return
to the village... as a man.

671
01:27:39,480 --> 01:27:41,778
When I leave you, Omri,

672
01:27:41,949 --> 01:27:45,612
I take you... as my nephew.

673
01:27:56,797 --> 01:27:58,128
Time to go, gentlemen.

674
01:28:02,069 --> 01:28:04,799
Easy, Darlin'. Easy, now.

675
01:28:04,972 --> 01:28:07,304
Don't y'all forget me.

676
01:28:08,942 --> 01:28:10,671
I won't.

677
01:28:12,713 --> 01:28:15,375
You look after yourself now,
Little Bear.

678
01:28:20,487 --> 01:28:22,978
And you, friend.

679
01:28:26,427 --> 01:28:29,521
- Goodbye, my friendly giants.
- Great Spirit?

680
01:28:29,697 --> 01:28:32,427
Yes, Little Bear?

681
01:28:32,599 --> 01:28:38,697
Tell me about the Onondaga gah.
Are we always a great people?

682
01:28:38,872 --> 01:28:41,272
You are always a great people...

683
01:28:45,646 --> 01:28:48,376
...but it's not always so good.

684
01:28:50,384 --> 01:28:55,151
- Things change for us?
- They will.

685
01:28:59,159 --> 01:29:00,990
We go.

686
01:29:23,217 --> 01:29:25,276
Now!

687
01:30:19,706 --> 01:30:22,937
"I will never know
where he is or how he is"

688
01:30:23,110 --> 01:30:25,271
"but I don't worry
about him any more. "

689
01:30:26,013 --> 01:30:28,277
"I think Little Bear
will have lots of children"

690
01:30:28,448 --> 01:30:31,383
"and he will teach them everything. "

691
01:30:31,552 --> 01:30:34,646
"He will always
take care of his people. "

692
01:30:36,123 --> 01:30:37,385
That's all.

693
01:30:37,558 --> 01:30:41,221
Very nice.
That's a good ending, Omri.

694
01:30:41,395 --> 01:30:42,987
Sam.

695
01:30:45,199 --> 01:30:47,394
"One day JFK was killed. "

696
01:30:47,568 --> 01:30:50,002
"He was shot on a street in Texas. "

697
01:30:50,170 --> 01:30:54,607
"My grandpa says that he
remembers exactly where he was... "

698
